      Emerging direction · typological encoding
    </div>
    <h1>Cross-lingual Interpretability</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      The same grounding question, where typology supplies the ground truth.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is an early direction, still taking shape — not a settled thesis line. It carries the
      question that runs through the rest of my work — <em>is a model's behaviour licensed by the
      genuine structure, or by a surface proxy that correlates with it?</em> — into a domain where
      the structure itself varies by language.
    </p>

    <h2>The idea</h2>
    <p>
      Different languages divide the labour of encoding meaning across <strong>morphology</strong>,
      <strong>word order</strong>, and <strong>context</strong> in very different proportions. A
      meaning that is morphologically explicit in one language (German case and verb inflection) is
      positionally fixed in a second (English's rigid SVO) and contextually implicit in a third
      (Chinese, which is largely isolating and marks tense, number, and even part of speech by
      context rather than form). If a model "succeeds" in all three, is it tracking the same
      underlying meaning, or three different surface cues that happen to correlate with it?
    </p>

    <p>
      The appeal is that <strong>language typology provides a natural ground truth</strong>. Pure
      causal-grounding work is often underdetermined because we cannot observe the true structure a
      model should be using. But we <em>do</em> know that Chinese lacks tense morphology, that German
      is verb-second with a discontinuous sentence bracket, that a Chinese character is roughly one
      morpheme while a German compound fragments into many subwords. Typology supplies the kind of
      planted, stipulated structure that the
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">Mini Causal Models</a> sandbox has to manufacture by
      hand.
    </p>

    <h2>Candidate probes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Tense without morphology.</strong> Where is tense represented for Chinese, which has
        no verb inflection — and is it a genuine tense representation, or a shortcut on surface
        markers like 了 or temporal adverbs?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tokenization as a confound.</strong> The token is not a cross-linguistically constant
        unit: a Chinese character ≈ a morpheme, while a German morpheme can be fragmented across
        subwords or split discontinuously (separable prefixes). Probing "at a token position"
        compares different things across languages.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Word order as a shortcut diagnostic.</strong> If a model handles German verb-final or
        V2 structure with the order scrambled and still succeeds, it is leaning on lexical cues, not
        genuine syntax — a falsification test in the spirit of Paper 1.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Category minimal pairs.</strong> Chinese lets the same form be noun or verb with no
        surface change (研究 = research / to research). Holding the form constant and flipping the
        category by context gives a controlled probe for whether the model reads genuine syntactic
        role or a surface cue.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Relation to the rest of the work</h2>
    <p>
      The method is the same toolkit used elsewhere — controls, disaggregation, and causal
      intervention — which is what keeps this from being a descriptive catalogue of cross-lingual
      differences. The connection to the
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">grounding question</a> is direct: a fluent surface use of
      a structure is not evidence that the structure is load-bearing. It also connects naturally to
      questions of implicitness and ambiguity in natural-language understanding, where what one
      language leaves implicit is exactly where misunderstanding tends to live.
    </p>

    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">
      Status: early-stage. Observations are being collected and stress-tested against the existing
      literature on multilingual interpretability, morphology-aware tokenization, and word-order
      sensitivity before any broader claims.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
